!! Overview

llm connect executes LLM-requested operations against the wiki store. This section describes the security boundaries, what is protected, and what is not.

!! API key storage

API keys are stored in wiki config tiddlers (`$:/config/rimir/llm-connect/providers/<name>/api-key`). They are visible to anyone with file access to the wiki. This is suitable for personal wikis or server wikis with authentication. API keys are never sent to the LLM — only to the respective provider API endpoint.

!! Tiddler protection — restricted wiki proxy

All tool wikitext executes against a restricted wiki proxy rather than the real `$tw.wiki`. The proxy is created via `Object.create($tw.wiki)` and overrides core access methods so protected tiddlers are invisible:

* `getTiddler`, `getTiddlerText`, `tiddlerExists`, `isShadowTiddler` — return undefined/false/default
* `filterTiddlers` — runs on real wiki, strips protected titles from results
* `each`, `forEachTiddler` — skip protected titles
* `addTiddler`, `deleteTiddler` — silently blocked for protected titles

This means wikitext transclusion, `<$list>` filters, and any custom tool code cannot access protected tiddlers — the proxy intercepts at every access point.

!! Protection filter layers

Protection is applied in two layers:

# ''Base filter'' — configured in Settings (default: `[tag[sensitive]] [all[shadows+tiddlers]prefix[$:/plugins/rimir/]]`). Always active for all chats and actions. Resettable to default via the settings UI.
# ''Per-chat filter'' — additional filter set via the shield icon in the chat header. Combined with the base filter. Stored in the `llm-protection-filter` field on the chat tiddler.

The default base filter protects:

* Tiddlers tagged `sensitive` — user-designated sensitive content
* All rimir plugin internals (`$:/plugins/rimir/`) — prevents the LLM from reading plugin source code, configuration, tool implementations, or API keys

!! Defense-in-depth

Tools that take an explicit `title` parameter (e.g. `get_tiddler`, `set_field`, `delete_tiddler`) check the title against the protection filter ''before'' wikitext execution. This provides a clear "Access denied" error message rather than a silent "not found". The proxy provides the second layer — even if a tool bypasses the title check (e.g. via wikitext transclusion), the proxy blocks access.

!! What is NOT protected

* ''The LLM conversation itself'' — messages are stored in the chat tiddler as plain JSON. Anyone with wiki access can read them.
* ''API traffic'' — requests go directly from the browser to the provider API over HTTPS. No data passes through a third-party proxy, but the provider can see all content.
* ''Tool execution'' — action-mode tools (`set_field`, `create_tiddler`, `delete_tiddler`) execute immediately. There is no confirmation step. An audit log is written to `$:/temp/rimir/llm-connect/write-log` but it is a temp tiddler (not persisted across reloads).
* ''System prompt and context'' — the LLM sees the system prompt, context template output, and all context attachments. It can be instructed via prompt injection in tiddler content.
* ''Unprotected tiddlers'' — any tiddler not matched by the protection filter is fully accessible to the LLM (read, modify, delete).

!! Multimodal file attachments

Files attached via the context filter are fetched from the server via XHR, base64-encoded in the browser, and sent inline in the API request. The max file size is enforced client-side (`$:/config/rimir/llm-connect/max-file-size`, default 20 MB). Files are not cached — they are re-fetched on each send.

!! Recommendations

* Tag sensitive tiddlers with `sensitive` or extend the base protection filter to cover additional content
* Use per-chat protection filters when working with a mix of sensitive and non-sensitive content
* Avoid storing secrets (passwords, tokens) in unprotected tiddlers — the LLM can read them via tools
* Review the audit log after LLM interactions that modify tiddlers
* Consider using read-only tool groups when the LLM only needs to search and read

